  						<table align=center cellpadding='3' width='85%'>
  <tr><td class='spti2'>PLAYER JOURNAL</td></tr>  <tr><td class='db'><font class='dbti'>My battles with giants</font> - Gardeltron Thundercrag</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'> </td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'><p>Giants roam widely across Antonica and Kunark.  Thank the Tribunal that
they seem to have never made it to Faydwer.  As a young shaman, I took great
pains to avoid the hill and sand giants I encountered.  As I grew in knowledge
and power I realized that it would be difficult for me to avoid them.  My first experience
actually hunting them was a series of skirmishes I had with giant skeletons in the
Mountains of Rathe.  My battles usually consisted of casting my best cold damage
on the giant skeleton, then running to a cliff wall or other location where I was sure
my back would not be exposed.  I then proceeded to hammer at the creature with
my enamaled black mace, or later, ebon war spear.  After a few blast of a cold spell and
lots of hand fighting, I usually was able to over power the giant skeleton.</p>

<p>One particular danger of these battles was the roaming cyclops and hill giants
that inhabited the region.  There was a particularly ferocious cyclops by the name of
Tarskuk who always seemed to find me while fighting giant skeletons.  If I was low on
life energy or tarried the least bit, this brute would quickly sudue me and send me back
to my bind point with a poignant sense of defeat.  When I went to Kunark, I found that
in the Frontier Mountains, a breed of giant lived that with great care and a little luck,
I could also battle.  However, I learned that if I first cast a poison or disease spell on
the mountain giant before fighting it, I was more likely to be succesful owing to its
weakened state.  I also began to cast on occasion spells that would slow the ability of
the giant to attack. This state of affairs remained the case
for many seasons.</p>

<p>In my 34th season, I was taught a spell that allowed me to summon a wolf spirit
to be my companion in battle.  By this time I was able to easily overcome giant skeletons,
 but with the assistance of a summoned wolf spirit, I was able to fight cyclops and moutain
giants more effectively.
 My basic strategy was much the same as I used with giant skeletons, only by enlisting the 
aid of the spirit, I began to regularly prevail.</p>

<p>By the time I reached my 39th season, I was regularly fighting with giants all across 
Norrath, including hill giants.  I learned new, extremely effective poison and debuff spells
that I could use, but I continued to enlist the aid of spirit wolves, especially the more vigilant
ones.  After overhearing a conversation among shamans in a tavern, I realized that I 
didn't need to enlist the aid of a spirit wolf to fight giants.  I adapted their technique to my 
own ends.  The technique is very powerful and I rarely am defeated, even by many of
the more powerful giants (however, I do not boast, because I have seen some extremely
powerful giants that I will not even attempt to fight).  First, I cast a spell that strikes the giant
as if by some powerful snake venom.  I then retreat quickly, and when a safe distance, cast an
enstill spell on the giant until its feet are rooted in the ground.  I then back off as far as possible,
so that I am just at the edge of my casting range.  By doing this, I am actually casting beyond the
giant's ability to directly detect me.  This makes it less likely to pull its feet free from the enstilling
spell.  I then quickly cast two disease spells whose effects are synergistic.  One is aptly labeled
scourge by shamans for obvious reasons.  This spell is followed by a spell that makes the giant's
malady even more insidious.  I then sit and meditate to recover my casting power, or use
the second spell in a series of spells that allows me to transform some of my life power into
mana.  When any of the aforementioned spells wear off, I immediately reapply it before the 
giant has a chance to do much damage.  Some giants are more resistant to my spells than others
so I usually end up engaging in some hand to hand combat and taking damage from the giant,
but more often than not, the giant quickly succombs to the combination of diseases and poisons
that I have cast on it.  In the end I usually either sit and meditate while I watch the rooted
brute die of disease or poison, or I chase the brute piercing its tail end with my spear
 as it flees after realizing too late that it bit off more than it could chew.</p></td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db2'><a href='view_profile.asp?Action=Journal&Id=33000'>Return to Gardeltron's Journal</a></td></tr>
